feat: implement complete Rust project infrastructure for POT provider (#3)
This PR establishes the complete Rust project infrastructure for the BgUtils POT Provider, setting up the foundation for rewriting the TypeScript implementation to Rust.
## What was implemented
### Core Project Structure - **Cargo.toml**: Complete project configuration with all necessary dependencies (Axum, Tokio, Serde, Clap, etc.) - **Module Architecture**: Organized into logical modules matching the TypeScript reference implementation: - `config`: Settings management with environment variable support - `error`: Comprehensive error handling using `thiserror` - `types`: Request/response structures matching the existing API - `session`: Session manager with caching and placeholder token generation - `server`: HTTP server implementation using Axum framework - `utils`: Version information and utility functions
### Binary Entry Points - **bgutil-pot-server**: HTTP server mode (default port 4416, equivalent to `main.ts`) - **bgutil-pot-generate**: Script mode for one-time token generation (equivalent to `generate_once.ts`)
Both binaries include proper CLI argument parsing and help documentation.
### Development Environment - **Testing Infrastructure**: Comprehensive unit and integration tests with 25 passing tests - **Quality Assurance**: All quality checks pass (compilation, formatting, linting, documentation) - **Development Tools**: VS Code configuration, Cargo settings, updated .gitignore - **Documentation**: Complete rustdoc documentation for all public APIs
### API Compatibility The Rust implementation maintains API compatibility with the TypeScript version:
```rust // POST /get_pot endpoint with matching request structure { "content_binding": "video_id", "proxy": "http://proxy:8080", "bypass_cache": false }
// Response matches TypeScript format { "poToken": "generated_token", "contentBinding": "video_id", "expiresAt": "2025-01-01T00:00:00Z" } ```
## Quality Metrics -
All 8 quality checks pass -
25 unit tests pass -
Zero clippy warnings -
Complete documentation coverage -
Cargo nextest compatibility
The project is now ready for implementing the actual POT token generation logic using BgUtils integration, while maintaining the existing API surface and operational modes.
Fixes #2.

build(devcontainer): switch devcontainer base from Python to Rust
- Switches the devcontainer configuration from Python to Rust, updates the base image and installed features accordingly, adjusts mounts for environment files, enhances Rust toolchain setup with additional tools, and updates VS Code extensions to focus on Rust and testing support.
Signed-off-by: Jim Chen <Jim@ChenJ.im>

test(nextest): introduce custom profiles for flexible test runs
- Add a nextest configuration file specifying custom test profiles for local development, CI, quick, and full test runs, including timeout, concurrency, retries, and reporting options.
Signed-off-by: Jim Chen <Jim@ChenJ.im>

chore(rust): update config files and dependencies for 2024 edition
- Remove Cargo.lock from the ignore list and add patterns to ignore environment variable files, log files, and JUnit XML test results. - Add a new .llvm-cov.toml configuration file to specify code coverage settings, including file exclusions, output formats, and report directories. - Add the Cargo.lock file, capturing all current dependency versions for the Rust project and recording a complete lock of the dependency graph. - Update Rust edition to 2024, revise package metadata, expand categories, add exclusions, and enhance documentation and lint configurations. Dependencies are updated to newer versions with additional features, and new development and packaging settings are included. - Add rustfmt configuration file setting edition to 2024 and max line width to 100.
Signed-off-by: Jim Chen <Jim@ChenJ.im>
